               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380514-name-1387" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1387" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1387" type="surname" value="CARROLL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1387" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM CARROLL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a surgeon, and live in Dean's-row, Walworth The prisoner was my footman—he came into my service on the 5th April—on the 9th of May I saw him in custody at the office, and spoon was produced, which belonged to me—the prisoner had the opportu<lb></lb>nity of taking it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380514-name-1388" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1388" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1388" type="surname" value="WOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1388" type="given" value="FREDERICK JOHN"></interp>FREDERICK JOHN WOOD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to Mr. Rosier, a pawnbroker I produce a table-spoon, which was pawned on the 16th of April—I be<lb></lb>lieve the prisoner to be the person, but I cannot swear positively to Him—this is the duplicate I gave to the person who pledged it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18380514-name-1389" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1389" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1389" type="surname" value="RAYHILL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18380514-name-1389" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN RAYHILL</persName>
                  </hi>. I took the prisoner into custody, offering to sell broken dessert fork to a pawnbroker—I took him to the station—he said it belonged to his aunt, at Bermondsey—I afterwards found he lived at the prosecutor's—I went there, and searched a box, which had the key in it and found in it the duplicate of the spoon pawned at Rosier's on the 16th of April.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CARROLL</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> The box the officer searched belonged to the prisoner—it was in the back kitchen—he went out with medicine that day, and was detained at a pawnbroker's, with the broken fork—this is my spoon—(<hi rend="italic">looking at it</hi>.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. I kept the duplicate in my box, because I was going to take it out again.</p>
